commits.message:
Standardize Dependabot configs on "Maven weekly, GitHub Actions monthly."

This includes:
- setting up Dependabot _at all_ for a few projects
- dropping GitHub Actions from weekly to monthly for the rest

My feeling on the latter is that GitHub Actions upgrades never feel urgent: Even when GitHub stopped supporting old versions of `actions/cache`, they gave plenty of warning. I'd also note that I don't think we've had trouble much (if ever?) with upgrades to GitHub Actions, so there's even less reason to fear batching of updates than usual. Given that, we might as well try to batch together as many updates as we can so as to marginally reduce toil. (And if an upgrade it ever truly urgent for security reasons, I expect that Dependabot would push us to it promptly, anyway, perhaps even for projects without a Dependabot config at all.)

RELNOTES=n/a
PiperOrigin-RevId: 739294702

Fix an AutoValue crash with `@AutoValue.CopyAnnotations(excluded=Missing.class)`.

If `Missing.class` is a class that does not exist, then with javac, at least, the `AnnotationValue` for it does not contain an `ErrorType`, as you might expect, but a `String`. We now ignore anything that is not a `DeclaredType`. Presumably the missing class will result in a compilation error anyway.

Fixes https://github.com/google/auto/issues/1901.

RELNOTES=Fixed a crash with `@AutoValue.CopyAnnotations(exclude=Missing.class)`, where `Missing` is a class that does not exist.
PiperOrigin-RevId: 739196666

Remove Error Prone type annotations dependency

This artifact has been merged with the other annotations artifact: https://github.com/google/error-prone/releases/tag/v2.37.0

PiperOrigin-RevId: 739001784

Bump Guava to 33.4.5.

Since that version of Guava [no longer depends on JSR-305](https://github.com/google/guava/releases/tag/v33.4.3), we need to make a change: Our tests [rely on having JSR-305 on the classpath](https://github.com/google/auto/pull/1899#issuecomment-2741155568), so we need to add it.

Also, since that version of Guava [depends on JSpecify](https://github.com/google/guava/releases/tag/v33.4.1), we presumably want to start shading JSpecify, just as we've done for other dependencies. I also confirmed (I hope correctly) that we can remove the shading configuration for JSR-305: That change makes no difference to `auto-value-HEAD-SNAPSHOT.jar` after the Guava upgrade, unlike before the Guava upgrade. Finally, I got to wondering if we still needed the Checker Framework shading, since Guava [doesn't depend on the Checker Framework annotations anymore](https://github.com/google/guava/releases/tag/v33.4.4), either. But I still see usages of those annotations in the final jar (in auto-common and perhaps elsewhere; I didn't look more after I found the first usage).
